<worksheet xml:id="lecture-notes-worksheet-quadratic-formula" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Using the Quadratic Formula</title>
        <theorem xml:id="lecture-notes-the-quadratic-formula">
        <title>The Quadratic Formula</title>

        <statement>
            <p>Let <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> be any real numbers with <m>a \ne 0</m>. Then the solutions to the quadratic equation <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m> can be found using the formula</p>
            <p><me>x = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}</me></p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <exercise xml:id="lecture-notes-solving-an-equation-with-two-real-roots" workspace="2in">
    <title>Solving an Equation with Two Real Roots</title>
    <statement>
        <p>Solve the equation <m>4x^2 + 13x + 10 = 0</m> using the Quadratic Formula.</p>
    </statement>
</exercise>

